highlights.description: Coming to UW Madison from East High School was quite a shift. Now I have to think about my race, my gender, my culture every day.
Being a student of color at UW is taking a toll on my mental health
In my big science classes at UW "you sort of drown in white people" and "I can be intimidated by people in discussion"
I love this white boy in my dorm because he asks questions and tries to learn
I live these issues about race every day, how are you going to tell me what I know and don't know about issues that affect black people?
Women telling stories about people ripping off or commenting negatively about their hijabs
Getting pulled over and putting my hands out the window so police officer would know I am not doing anything, my white friend not understanding
What can an ally to non-white people do? Open up your circles, understand, and lift up their voices
What should the Mayor of Madison hear? This conversation with women of color.
It's good to have conversations like this because you learn you really have supportive people
I hope white people don't listen to this and feel like their issues aren't serious, too. They are. Just realize you are still privileged.
Holding truth to power by sharing these lived experiences
